  <h2>The Employee Scheduling Software Trap</h2>
  
  <p>Most contractors think they need "employee scheduling software." So they sign up for:</p>
  
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Homebase</strong> — Good for shift-based retail, terrible for service calls</li>
    <li><strong>When I Work</strong> — Requires every tech to download an app and check it constantly</li>
    <li><strong>Deputy</strong> — Powerful, but overkill for teams under 20 people</li>
    <li><strong>Sling</strong> — Better for restaurants than field service</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p>These tools solve a different problem. They're built for retail stores and restaurants with predictable shifts, not service businesses with dynamic schedules.</p>
  
  <p><strong>The real issue isn't employee scheduling — it's workflow automation.</strong></p>
  
  <p>You don't just need to schedule your techs. You need to:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Capture the lead when they call or submit a form</li>
    <li>Qualify the job (emergency vs. routine, budget, location)</li>
    <li>Check tech availability automatically</li>
    <li>Book the appointment</li>
    <li>Notify the tech</li>
    <li>Send the customer a confirmation</li>
    <li>Update your CRM</li>
    <li>Send a reminder the day before</li>
  </ol>
  
  <p><mark>That's not employee scheduling software. That's business automation.</mark></p>

