  <h2>What Actually Works: Workflow Automation + CRM</h2>
  
  <p>The contractors I've talked to in Wichita who have this figured out aren't using "employee scheduling software." They're using workflow automation that connects their phone, website, and CRM.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Here's how it works:</strong></p>
  
  <p><strong>1. Lead Capture (Automated)</strong></p>
  <p>Customer calls your number or submits a form on your website. An AI assistant answers, qualifies the job, and captures:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Name, phone, email</li>
    <li>Problem description</li>
    <li>Urgency (emergency vs. can wait)</li>
    <li>Preferred time</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p><strong>2. Scheduling (Automated)</strong></p>
  <p>The system checks your CRM (monday.com, Hubspot, Pipedrive — whatever you use) and finds the first available tech who can handle the job. Books it automatically.</p>
  
  <p><strong>3. Notifications (Automated)</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Tech gets a text with job details</li>
    <li>Customer gets an email confirmation</li>
    <li>CRM updates automatically</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p><strong>4. Follow-Up (Automated)</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Reminder text the day before</li>
    <li>Post-job follow-up for reviews</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p><strong>Your involvement: Zero.</strong></p>
  
  <p>You can review bookings in your CRM whenever you want, but you don't have to manually schedule anything unless it's a special case.</p>

